48-23.978667-70.613333-4.352-70.613333 32.256v126.208l-0.256 4.309333c-2.218667 21.504-20.437333 38.186667-42.410667 40.021333l-17.194667 1.706667c-173.994667 20.949333-253.824 136.405333-253.824 304.554667 86.997333-89.557333 163.925333-105.386667 270.933334-107.861334a42.026667 42.026667 0 0 1 42.752 42.24v125.226667c0 34.56 38.272 53.845333 65.706666 35.925333l5.376-4.096 304.426667-272.213333a42.666667 42.666667 0 0 0 2.986667-60.714667l-3.413334-3.285333-304.469333-264.277333z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div><!----> <!----> <!----><div data-v-a0ebfd13="" class="icon"><svg data-v-a0ebfd13="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify" width="1em" height="1em" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Clip"><path d="M239.08352 319.0784a188.17024 188.17024 0 0 1 376.29952 0v0.16384l4.62848 347.62752v0.08192a112.64 112.64 0 0 1-156.0576 105.63584 112.55808 112.55808 0 0 1-68.97664-105.39008V315.14624a36.864 36.864 0 1 1 73.728 0v352.99328a38.83008 38.83008 0 1 0 77.57824 0v-0.16384l-4.58752-347.58656V320.3072a114.4832 114.4832 0 0 0-228.88448-0.4096l4.5056 347.58656a190.13632 190.13632 0 1 0 380.3136 0l0.4096-334.39744a36.864 36.864 0 1 1 73.728 0.08192l-0.4096 334.31552a263.90528 263.90528 0 0 1-450.43712 186.61376 263.86432 263.86432 0 0 1-77.29152-186.368l-4.54656-347.50464v-1.10592z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <div data-v-a0ebfd13="" class="file-count">1</div></div><!----></div></div></div> <div data-v-dab930b3="" class="header-right desktop-no-drag"> <!----></div></div> <div data-v-dab930b3="" class="layout-content-main"> <div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-page chat"><!----> <div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-detail-content"><div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-detail-main" style="--goal-info-bar-reserved-height: 0px;"><div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-content-container"><div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-content-list"><!----><div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-content-item chat-content-item-user" data-archer-id="19f3d5d7-0222-8c4e-8000-0a7b9a1ad989"><!----> <div data-v-2788030a="" data-v-6f8c130e="" class="segment segment-user"><!----> <div data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-container" dir="auto"> <!----> <!----> <div data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-content"><div data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-content-box"> <div data-v-d3915d44="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="user-content"><!----> Types of Welded Joints, Joint Preparation, and Applications (as per AISC &amp; ASTM)

Note: AISC provides the design requirements for structural steel welding through the Steel Construction Manual and Specification for Structural Steel Buildings. Material specifications are covered by ASTM International, while welding procedures and symbols are primarily governed by American Welding Society, which is referenced by AISC.

1. Butt Joint (Groove Joint)
5
Definition

A butt joint joins two steel plates lying in the same plane. The weld is deposited in the groove between the plate edges.

Common Groove Types
Square Groove
Single V-Groove
Double V-Groove
Single Bevel Groove
Double Bevel Groove
Single U-Groove
Double U-Groove
Single J-Groove
Double J-Groove
Joint Preparation
Clean surfaces (remove rust, oil, paint, moisture).
Machine or flame-cut groove edges.
Maintain proper root opening.
Provide root face (land) if required.
Align plates accurately.
Tack weld before final welding.
Applications
Building columns
Beam splices
Plate girders
Pressure vessels
Bridges
Heavy structural members
2. Lap Joint
5
Definition

A lap joint is formed when one plate overlaps another and they are welded together, usually using fillet welds.

Joint Preparation
Clean overlap surfaces.
Ensure adequate overlap length.
Clamp plates firmly.
Tack weld before completing weld.
Applications
Thin steel plates
Cover plates
Secondary steel members
Bracing connections
Repair work
3. Tee Joint (T-Joint)
6
Definition

A tee joint is formed when one member is positioned at approximately 90° to another, creating a "T" shape.

Joint Preparation
Prepare groove if full penetration is required.
Clean contact surfaces.
Ensure correct alignment.
Use backing bar when specified.
Tack weld before final welding.
Applications
Column-to-base plate connections
Beam-to-column stiffeners
Connection plates
Built-up sections
Box girders
4. Corner Joint
5
Definition

A corner joint joins two members at approximately 90° to form an L-shaped corner.

Joint Preparation
Clean plate edges.
Prepare groove for thick sections.
Maintain correct fit-up.
Use clamps to prevent distortion.
Applications
Box sections
Frames
Steel tanks
Structural enclosures
Fabricated equipment
5. Edge Joint
5
Definition

An edge joint joins two parallel plate edges lying side by side. It is generally used where the joint carries little structural load.

Joint Preparation
Align edges carefully.
Clean surfaces.
Clamp plates to prevent movement.
Prepare groove if necessary.
Applications
Sheet metal work
Covers
Tanks
Light-duty fabrication
Non-load-bearing components
General Joint Preparation Requirements (AISC/AWS)

Before welding:

Remove rust, oil, grease, paint, scale, and moisture.
Prepare groove according to approved welding procedure.
Maintain proper root opening.
Maintain correct groove angle.
Ensure proper fit-up and alignment.
Use tack welds where necessary.
Use backing bars if specified.
Select proper welding electrode or wire.
Control preheat and interpass temperature when required.
Inspect joint before welding.
Typical Groove Preparations
Groove Type	Typical Included Angle	Common Use
Square Groove	0°	Thin plates
Single V	60°	Medium thickness
Double V	60° each side	Thick plates
Single Bevel	30–45°	One-sided access
Double Bevel	30–45°	Thick sections
Single U	Curved groove	Very thick plates
Double U	Curved both sides	Heavy fabrication
Single J	J-shaped edge	Thick members
Double J	J both sides	Heavy structural welds
Summary Table
Joint Type	Typical Weld	Strength	Common Applications
Butt Joint	Groove Weld	Very High	Beam splices, column splices, bridges
Lap Joint	Fillet Weld	Moderate	Thin plates, cover plates
Tee Joint	Fillet/Groove	High	Stiffeners, base plates, built-up sections
Corner Joint	Fillet/Groove	Moderate–High	Frames, tanks, box sections
Edge Joint	Edge Weld	Low	Sheet metal, covers, light fabrication
AISC/ASTM Notes
AISC specifies the design, detailing, and strength requirements for welded structural connections.
ASTM specifies the material requirements for structural steel (e.g., ASTM A36, ASTM A572, ASTM A992).
Welding procedures, prequalification, inspection, and acceptance criteria are defined in AWS D1.1, which is referenced by AISC for structural steel welding.

This content is suitable for seminar or PPT preparation, and each joint type can be presented on a separate slide with its image, definition, joint preparation, and applications.</div> <!----> <!----> <!----> <!----></div>  <!----> <!----> <!----> <!---->   <!----> <div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="okc-cards-container"><!----> <!----> <!----> <!----> <!----></div> <!----> <!----> <!----> <div data-v-b1bd13bb="" data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-user-action-row"><div data-v-b1bd13bb="" class="segment-user-actions"> <div data-v-351fdc4e="" data-v-b1bd13bb="" class="simple-button size-small"><svg data-v-351fdc4e="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify simple-button-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Edit"><path d="M736.085333 222.592a46.165333 46.165333 0 0 1 65.322667 65.28L336.426667 752.938667a132.266667 132.266667 0 0 1-61.44 34.773333l-51.541334 12.885333 12.885334-51.541333a132.266667 132.266667 0 0 1 34.773333-61.44L736.085333 222.592z m32.682667-90.325333c-32.64 0-63.914667 12.970667-86.997333 36.010666L216.832 633.258667a209.066667 209.066667 0 0 0-55.04 97.152l-28.373333 113.621333a38.4 38.4 0 0 0 46.549333 46.549333l113.621333-28.416a209.066667 209.066667 0 0 0 97.152-54.997333l361.813334-361.813333 103.168-103.125334A122.965333 122.965333 0 0 0 768.768 132.266667zM512 814.933333a38.4 38.4 0 1 0 0 76.8h298.666667a38.4 38.4 0 1 0 0-76.8h-298.666667z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <span data-v-351fdc4e="">Edit</span></div> <div data-v-351fdc4e="" data-v-92afdd37="" data-v-b1bd13bb="" class="simple-button size-small"><svg data-v-351fdc4e="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify simple-button-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Copy"><path d="M725.333333 302.933333a166.4 166.4 0 0 1 166.4 166.4v256a166.4 166.4 0 0 1-166.4 166.4h-256A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 302.933333 725.333333v-256A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 469.333333 302.933333h256z m-256 76.8A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 379.733333 469.333333v256c0 49.493333 40.106667 89.6 89.6 89.6h256a89.6 89.6 0 0 0 89.6-89.6v-256A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 725.333333 379.733333h-256z" fill="currentColor"></path><path d="M554.666667 132.266667a166.4 166.4 0 0 1 144.128 83.2 38.4 38.4 0 0 1-66.517334 38.4A89.514667 89.514667 0 0 0 554.666667 209.066667H298.666667A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 209.066667 298.666667v256c0 33.109333 17.92 62.08 44.8 77.653333a38.4 38.4 0 0 1-38.4 66.474667A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 132.266667 554.666667V298.666667A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 298.666667 132.266667h256z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <span data-v-351fdc4e="">Copy</span></div> <div data-v-351fdc4e="" data-v-b1bd13bb="" class="simple-button size-small"><svg data-v-351fdc4e="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify simple-button-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Share_a"><path d="M386.218667 247.850667c0-102.4 120.405333-157.397333 197.76-90.282667l304.426666 264.32a119.466667 119.466667 0 0 1 1.365334 179.285333l-304.469334 272.170667c-76.970667 68.778667-199.082667 14.122667-199.082666-89.088v-89.173333c-33.024 2.261333-59.306667 6.826667-83.2 15.36-30.592 10.88-61.866667 29.952-98.602667 67.712a76.8 76.8 0 0 1-131.84-53.504c0-98.645333 24.106667-190.976 83.712-261.888 55.253333-65.792 133.973333-104.789333 229.930667-117.845334V247.850667z m147.413333-32.256c-27.648-23.978667-70.613333-4.352-70.613333 32.256v126.208l-0.256 4.309333c-2.218667 21.504-20.437333 38.186667-42.410667 40.021333l-17.194667 1.706667c-173.994667 20.949333-253.824 136.405333-253.824 304.554667 86.997333-89.557333 163.925333-105.386667 270.933334-107.861334a42.026667 42.026667 0 0 1 42.752 42.24v125.226667c0 34.56 38.272 53.845333 65.706666 35.925333l5.376-4.096 304.426667-272.213333a42.666667 42.666667 0 0 0 2.986667-60.714667l-3.413334-3.285333-304.469333-264.277333z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <span data-v-351fdc4e="">Share</span></div> <!----></div> <!----></div>   <!----> <!----> <!----> <!----></div></div></div></div><div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="chat-content-item chat-content-item-assistant" data-archer-id="19f3d5d7-0222-8c4e-8000-0a7bdf9f62e6"><!----> <div data-v-2788030a="" data-v-6f8c130e="" class="segment segment-assistant"><div data-v-88be9e2e="" data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-avatar"><div data-v-88be9e2e="" class="avatar"><canvas data-v-b81624a4="" data-v-88be9e2e="" class="rive-container" width="70" height="70" style="width: 56px; height: 56px;"></canvas></div></div> <div data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-container" dir="auto"> <!----> <!----> <div data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-content"><div data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-content-box"> <div data-v-e2ab115e="" class="container-block"><div data-v-e2ab115e="" class="block-item"><div data-v-763ce8f9=""><div data-v-9606ddcc="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="toolcall-container default toolcall-image_search"><div data-v-bc9c95fe="" data-v-9606ddcc="" class="toolcall-title-container default"><div data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-name"><svg data-v-bc9c95fe="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify toolcall-title-name-icon" width="1em" height="1em" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Search"><path d="M491.52 155.648a348.16 348.16 0 0 1 270.86848 566.8864l123.82208 123.86304a36.864 36.864 0 1 1-52.10112 52.10112l-123.86304-123.82208A348.16 348.16 0 1 1 491.52 155.648z m0 622.592a274.432 274.432 0 1 0 0-548.864 274.432 274.432 0 0 0 0 548.864z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <span data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-name-text">Search images</span></div> <span data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-container-content"><span data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-container-text">butt joint welding types diagram square V groove lap joint fillet weld diagram Tee joint T-joint welding diagram structural steel corner joint welding diagram box section edge joint welding diagram sheet metal</span> </span> <div data-v-bc9c95fe="" class="toolcall-title-container-extra"><span data-v-9606ddcc="" need-upgrade="false">10 results</span> <svg data-v-bc9c95fe="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify toolcall-title-container-extra-arrow" width="1em" height="1em" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Right_b"><path d="M681.00096 549.23264a36.864 36.864 0 0 0-0.08192-52.0192L395.22304 211.47648a36.864 36.864 0 1 0-52.14208 52.10112l259.6864 259.72736-259.76832 261.69344a36.864 36.864 0 0 0 52.30592 51.93728l285.696-287.744z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div> <!----></div></div></div></div> <!----><!----> <div data-v-3b9ae98b="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="markdown-container"><div data-v-3b9ae98b="" class="markdown"><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Here's a comprehensive, visually-supported guide to <strong class="">Types of Welded Joints, Joint Preparation, and Applications</strong> as per <strong>AISC (American Institute of Steel Construction)</strong> and <strong class="">ASTM (ASTM International)</strong> standards.</div><hr><h2>Overview</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">AISC provides the design requirements for structural steel welding through the <em>Steel Construction Manual</em> and <em>Specification for Structural Steel Buildings</em>. Material specifications are covered by ASTM International, while welding procedures and symbols are primarily governed by the <strong>American Welding Society (AWS)</strong>, which is referenced by AISC.</div><hr><h2 class="">1. Butt Joint (Groove Joint)</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Definition:</strong> A butt joint joins two steel plates lying in the same plane. The weld is deposited in the groove between the plate edges.</div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Common Groove Types:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Square Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Single V-Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Double V-Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Single Bevel Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Double Bevel Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Single U-Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Double U-Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Single J-Groove</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Double J-Groove</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><div data-v-d2fbbf55="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="pua-ref-renderer pua-ref-renderer--image"><div data-v-63019ecb="" data-v-d2fbbf55="" class="pua-ref-image-block"><div data-v-112f5d34="" data-v-bcbe198e="" data-v-63019ecb="" class="carousel-container carousel-container-card pua-ref-image-multi-carousel"><!----> <!----> <div data-v-112f5d34="" class="carousel-scroll"><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Welding Joint Types Explained With Diagrams" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/d36b8d8b2a72a1a8769d2c7eb5d2f3c4defde7f6.jpg"> <!----></span></div><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="The Different Types of Welding Joints: A Comprehensive Guide" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/a389da2cdfdf6597b884c244003040462be848a0"> <!----></span></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Joint Preparation:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clean surfaces (remove rust, oil, paint, moisture)</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Machine or flame-cut groove edges</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Maintain proper root opening</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Provide root face (land) if required</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Align plates accurately</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Tack weld before final welding</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Applications:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Building columns</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Beam splices</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Plate girders</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Pressure vessels</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Bridges</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Heavy structural members</div></li></ul><hr><h2>2. Lap Joint</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Definition:</strong> A lap joint is formed when one plate overlaps another and they are welded together, usually using fillet welds.</div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><div data-v-d2fbbf55="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="pua-ref-renderer pua-ref-renderer--image"><div data-v-63019ecb="" data-v-d2fbbf55="" class="pua-ref-image-block"><div data-v-112f5d34="" data-v-bcbe198e="" data-v-63019ecb="" class="carousel-container carousel-container-card pua-ref-image-multi-carousel"><!----> <!----> <div data-v-112f5d34="" class="carousel-scroll"><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Welding Joint Types: Butt, Lap, Tee, Edge Joints &amp; More | UTI" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/95357b56272a14a6694e1d0ee5dafc534b8fcbd0.webp"> <!----></span></div><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Fillet Welded Joints - A Review of the Practicalities - TWI" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/57d1b75deb12c10146f629d786314f542e92403e.gif"> <!----></span></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Joint Preparation:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clean overlap surfaces</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Ensure adequate overlap length</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clamp plates firmly</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Tack weld before completing weld</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Applications:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Thin steel plates</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Cover plates</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Secondary steel members</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Bracing connections</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Repair work</div></li></ul><hr><h2>3. Tee Joint (T-Joint)</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Definition:</strong> A tee joint is formed when one member is positioned at approximately 90° to another, creating a "T" shape.</div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><div data-v-d2fbbf55="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="pua-ref-renderer pua-ref-renderer--image"><div data-v-63019ecb="" data-v-d2fbbf55="" class="pua-ref-image-block"><div data-v-112f5d34="" data-v-bcbe198e="" data-v-63019ecb="" class="carousel-container carousel-container-card pua-ref-image-multi-carousel"><!----> <!----> <div data-v-112f5d34="" class="carousel-scroll"><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Welding Joint Types: Butt, Lap, Tee, Edge Joints &amp; More | UTI" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/08b730d19e97c8e4531353c52734903a8abf193e.webp"> <!----></span></div><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Welding-TEE FILLET JOINT ~ Ourengineeringlabs" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/1d761adbd449f964649715587f7763ab995dc6ca.jpg"> <!----></span></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Joint Preparation:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Prepare groove if full penetration is required</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clean contact surfaces</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Ensure correct alignment</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Use backing bar when specified</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Tack weld before final welding</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Applications:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Column-to-base plate connections</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Beam-to-column stiffeners</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Connection plates</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Built-up sections</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Box girders</div></li></ul><hr><h2 class="">4. Corner Joint</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Definition:</strong> A corner joint joins two members at approximately 90° to form an L-shaped corner.</div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><div data-v-d2fbbf55="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="pua-ref-renderer pua-ref-renderer--image"><div data-v-63019ecb="" data-v-d2fbbf55="" class="pua-ref-image-block"><div data-v-112f5d34="" data-v-bcbe198e="" data-v-63019ecb="" class="carousel-container carousel-container-card pua-ref-image-multi-carousel"><!----> <!----> <div data-v-112f5d34="" class="carousel-scroll"><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="mechanical engineering - Advice on suitability of corner joints in welded  frame - Engineering Stack Exchange" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/f48268f4ac90858565f4155637e971acad44f056.png"> <!----></span></div><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Corner Joint Welding: All You Need To Know" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/e2de61a4f05c8d0aa21db02e7d7388114104170e.png"> <!----></span></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Joint Preparation:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clean plate edges</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Prepare groove for thick sections</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Maintain correct fit-up</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Use clamps to prevent distortion</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Applications:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Box sections</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Frames</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Steel tanks</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Structural enclosures</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Fabricated equipment</div></li></ul><hr><h2>5. Edge Joint</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Definition:</strong> An edge joint joins two parallel plate edges lying side by side. It is generally used where the joint carries little structural load.</div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><div data-v-d2fbbf55="" data-v-763ce8f9="" class="pua-ref-renderer pua-ref-renderer--image"><div data-v-63019ecb="" data-v-d2fbbf55="" class="pua-ref-image-block"><div data-v-112f5d34="" data-v-bcbe198e="" data-v-63019ecb="" class="carousel-container carousel-container-card pua-ref-image-multi-carousel"><!----> <!----> <div data-v-112f5d34="" class="carousel-scroll"><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Edge Weld Symbols – Interpretation of Metal Fab Drawings" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/778658dab43fc833c4b31d03991deb9d1332944c.png"> <!----></span></div><div data-v-bcbe198e="" class="pua-ref-image-card"><span data-v-0fac845b="" data-v-bcbe198e="" class="image-wrapper pua-ref-image-card__img"><!----> <img data-v-0fac845b="" class="image-main is-cover" loading="eager" alt="Types of Welding Joints Explained | YesWelder" src="./Welded Joint Types &amp; Prep - Kimi_files/411487f05525bfbd364bbfea02fdc6927fa2002f.webp"> <!----></span></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Joint Preparation:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Align edges carefully</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clean surfaces</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Clamp plates to prevent movement</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Prepare groove if necessary</div></li></ul><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Applications:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Sheet metal work</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Covers</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Tanks</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Light-duty fabrication</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Non-load-bearing components</div></li></ul><hr><h2>General Joint Preparation Requirements (AISC/AWS)</h2><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Before welding:</strong></div><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Remove rust, oil, grease, paint, scale, and moisture</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Prepare groove according to approved welding procedure</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Maintain proper root opening</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Maintain correct groove angle</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Ensure proper fit-up and alignment</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Use tack welds where necessary</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Use backing bars if specified</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Select proper welding electrode or wire</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Control preheat and interpass temperature when required</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Inspect joint before welding</div></li></ul><hr><h2 class="">Typical Groove Preparations</h2><div data-v-01af594f="" data-v-3b9ae98b="" class="table markdown-table"><div data-v-13fde6a9="" data-v-01af594f="" class="sticky-release" style="--sticky-header-height: 42.5px;"><div data-v-13fde6a9="" class="sticky-release-rail"><div data-v-13fde6a9="" class="sticky-release-header" style="top: 0px;"><header data-v-01af594f="" class="table-actions"><div data-v-01af594f="" class="table-actions-content"><span data-v-01af594f="" class="table-title">Table</span> <span data-v-868ea423="" data-v-01af594f=""><div data-v-1005b780="" data-v-868ea423="" class="icon-button" style="width: 32px; height: 32px;"><svg data-v-1005b780="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Copy"><path d="M725.333333 302.933333a166.4 166.4 0 0 1 166.4 166.4v256a166.4 166.4 0 0 1-166.4 166.4h-256A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 302.933333 725.333333v-256A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 469.333333 302.933333h256z m-256 76.8A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 379.733333 469.333333v256c0 49.493333 40.106667 89.6 89.6 89.6h256a89.6 89.6 0 0 0 89.6-89.6v-256A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 725.333333 379.733333h-256z" fill="currentColor"></path><path d="M554.666667 132.266667a166.4 166.4 0 0 1 144.128 83.2 38.4 38.4 0 0 1-66.517334 38.4A89.514667 89.514667 0 0 0 554.666667 209.066667H298.666667A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 209.066667 298.666667v256c0 33.109333 17.92 62.08 44.8 77.653333a38.4 38.4 0 0 1-38.4 66.474667A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 132.266667 554.666667V298.666667A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 298.666667 132.266667h256z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <div data-v-8e9e3110="" data-v-1005b780="" class="kimi-tooltip tooltip-bottom icon-button-tooltip bottom">Copy</div></div></span> <div data-v-1005b780="" data-v-01af594f="" class="icon-button table-actions-icon" style="width: 32px; height: 32px;"><svg data-v-1005b780="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Download"><path d="M512 126.976a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864 36.864v347.91424l119.11168-119.11168a36.864 36.864 0 1 1 52.14208 52.14208l-182.0672 182.02624a36.864 36.864 0 0 1-52.10112 0l-182.0672-182.02624a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 52.14208-52.14208l119.11168 119.11168V163.84a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864-36.864zM184.32 564.71552a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864 36.864v145.65376a35.96288 35.96288 0 0 0 35.96288 35.96288h509.70624a35.96288 35.96288 0 0 0 35.96288-35.96288v-145.65376a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 73.728 0v145.65376a109.69088 109.69088 0 0 1-109.69088 109.69088H257.14688A109.69088 109.69088 0 0 1 147.456 747.23328v-145.65376a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864-36.864z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <!----></div><!----></div></header></div></div></div> <div data-v-01af594f="" class="table-container"><table data-v-01af594f=""><thead data-v-01af594f=""><tr data-v-01af594f=""><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Groove Type</th><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Typical Included Angle</th><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Common Use</th></tr></thead> <tbody data-v-01af594f=""><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Square Groove</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">0°</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Thin plates</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Single V</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">60°</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Medium thickness</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Double V</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">60° each side</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Thick plates</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Single Bevel</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">30–45°</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">One-sided access</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Double Bevel</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">30–45°</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Thick sections</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Single U</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Curved groove</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Very thick plates</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Double U</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Curved both sides</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Heavy fabrication</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Single J</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">J-shaped edge</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Thick members</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Double J</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">J both sides</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Heavy structural welds</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div><hr><h2>Summary Table</h2><div data-v-01af594f="" data-v-3b9ae98b="" class="table markdown-table"><div data-v-13fde6a9="" data-v-01af594f="" class="sticky-release" style="--sticky-header-height: 42.5px;"><div data-v-13fde6a9="" class="sticky-release-rail"><div data-v-13fde6a9="" class="sticky-release-header" style="top: 0px;"><header data-v-01af594f="" class="table-actions"><div data-v-01af594f="" class="table-actions-content"><span data-v-01af594f="" class="table-title">Table</span> <span data-v-868ea423="" data-v-01af594f=""><div data-v-1005b780="" data-v-868ea423="" class="icon-button" style="width: 32px; height: 32px;"><svg data-v-1005b780="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Copy"><path d="M725.333333 302.933333a166.4 166.4 0 0 1 166.4 166.4v256a166.4 166.4 0 0 1-166.4 166.4h-256A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 302.933333 725.333333v-256A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 469.333333 302.933333h256z m-256 76.8A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 379.733333 469.333333v256c0 49.493333 40.106667 89.6 89.6 89.6h256a89.6 89.6 0 0 0 89.6-89.6v-256A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 725.333333 379.733333h-256z" fill="currentColor"></path><path d="M554.666667 132.266667a166.4 166.4 0 0 1 144.128 83.2 38.4 38.4 0 0 1-66.517334 38.4A89.514667 89.514667 0 0 0 554.666667 209.066667H298.666667A89.6 89.6 0 0 0 209.066667 298.666667v256c0 33.109333 17.92 62.08 44.8 77.653333a38.4 38.4 0 0 1-38.4 66.474667A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 132.266667 554.666667V298.666667A166.4 166.4 0 0 1 298.666667 132.266667h256z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <div data-v-8e9e3110="" data-v-1005b780="" class="kimi-tooltip tooltip-bottom icon-button-tooltip bottom">Copy</div></div></span> <div data-v-1005b780="" data-v-01af594f="" class="icon-button table-actions-icon" style="width: 32px; height: 32px;"><svg data-v-1005b780="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Download"><path d="M512 126.976a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864 36.864v347.91424l119.11168-119.11168a36.864 36.864 0 1 1 52.14208 52.14208l-182.0672 182.02624a36.864 36.864 0 0 1-52.10112 0l-182.0672-182.02624a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 52.14208-52.14208l119.11168 119.11168V163.84a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864-36.864zM184.32 564.71552a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864 36.864v145.65376a35.96288 35.96288 0 0 0 35.96288 35.96288h509.70624a35.96288 35.96288 0 0 0 35.96288-35.96288v-145.65376a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 73.728 0v145.65376a109.69088 109.69088 0 0 1-109.69088 109.69088H257.14688A109.69088 109.69088 0 0 1 147.456 747.23328v-145.65376a36.864 36.864 0 0 1 36.864-36.864z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg> <!----></div><!----></div></header></div></div></div> <div data-v-01af594f="" class="table-container"><table data-v-01af594f=""><thead data-v-01af594f=""><tr data-v-01af594f=""><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Joint Type</th><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Typical Weld</th><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Strength</th><th data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Common Applications</th></tr></thead> <tbody data-v-01af594f=""><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Butt Joint</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Groove Weld</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Very High</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Beam splices, column splices, bridges</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Lap Joint</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Fillet Weld</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Moderate</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Thin plates, cover plates</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Tee Joint</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Fillet/Groove</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">High</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Stiffeners, base plates, built-up sections</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Corner Joint</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Fillet/Groove</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Moderate–High</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Frames, tanks, box sections</td></tr><tr data-v-01af594f=""><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Edge Joint</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left">Edge Weld</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Low</td><td data-v-01af594f="" align="left" class="">Sheet metal, covers, light fabrication</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div><hr><h2 class="">AISC/ASTM Notes</h2><ul start="1"><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>AISC</strong> specifies the design, detailing, and strength requirements for welded structural connections.</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>ASTM</strong> specifies the material requirements for structural steel (e.g., ASTM A36, ASTM A572, ASTM A992).</div></li><li><div class="paragraph" dir="auto">Welding procedures, prequalification, inspection, and acceptance criteria are defined in <strong>AWS D1.1</strong>, which is referenced by AISC for structural steel welding.</div></li></ul><hr><blockquote><div class="paragraph" dir="auto"><strong>Note:</strong> This content is suitable for seminar or PPT preparation, and each joint type can be presented on a separate slide with its image, definition, joint preparation, and applications.</div></blockquote></div></div> <!----> <!----> <!----></div>  <!----> <!----> <!----> <!---->   <!----> <div data-v-6f8c130e="" class="okc-cards-container"><!----> <!----> <!----> <!----> <!----></div> <!----> <!----> <!----> <div data-v-b1bd13bb="" data-v-2788030a="" class="segment-assistant-actions"><div data-v-b1bd13bb="" class="segment-assistant-actions-content"> <!----> <!----> <!----><div data-v-1005b780="" data-v-b1bd13bb="" class="icon-button" style="width: 28px; height: 28px;"><svg data-v-1005b780="" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" role="img" class="iconify" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 1024 1024" name="Copy"><path d="M725.333333 302.933333a